$$
\text{To solve this problem, we can apply Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle, which states that the product of the uncertainties in position (\(\Delta x\)) and momentum (\(\Delta p\)) is greater than or equal to Planck's constant (\(h\)) divided by \(4\pi\). Mathematically, this is expressed as:}
\\
\Delta x \cdot \Delta p \geq \frac{h}{4\pi}
\\
\text{Given:}
\\
\Delta x = 20 \, \text{pm} = 20 \times 10^{-12} \, \text{m}
\\
h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J} \cdot \text{s}
\\
\text{We need to find } \Delta p (\text{uncertainty in momentum}), \text{which can be expressed as } \Delta p = m \cdot \Delta v (\text{uncertainty in velocity}), \text{where } m \text{ is the mass of the electron}
\\
m_{\text{electron}} = 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \text{kg}
\\
\text{Rearranging the Uncertainty Principle for } \Delta v, \text{we get:}
\\
\Delta v = \frac{h}{4\pi m \Delta x}
\\
\text{Plugging in the values:}
\\
\Delta v = \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34}}{4\pi \times 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \times 20 \times 10^{-12}}
\\
\Delta v \approx 2.21 \times 10^6 \, \text{m/s}
\\
\text{Therefore, the uncertainty in the electron's speed is approximately } \boxed{2.21 \times 10^6 \, \text{m/s}}.
$$
